            <section class="mt-8 prose">
              <h2>How this pediatric maintenance fluids calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool implements the classic Holliday–Segar method (the
                “4-2-1 rule”) to estimate maintenance IV fluid requirements in
                children, and optionally adds a dehydration deficit over a
                chosen time period. It is intended for quick bedside checks
                alongside local protocols.
              </p>

              <h3>1. Holliday–Segar method (4-2-1 rule)</h3>
              <p>
                The method assumes that fluid needs are proportional to energy
                expenditure. Hourly maintenance rate is calculated from weight
                in kilograms:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p><strong>Hourly maintenance rate (mL/hr)</strong></p>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    For weight ≤ 10 kg: \( 4 \text{ mL/kg/hr} \times
                    \text{weight (kg)} \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    For 10–20 kg: \( 40 \text{ mL/hr} + 2 \text{ mL/kg/hr}
                    \times (\text{weight} - 10) \)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    For &gt; 20 kg: \( 60 \text{ mL/hr} + 1 \text{ mL/kg/hr}
                    \times (\text{weight} - 20) \)
                  </li>
                </ul>
                <p>
                  <strong>Daily maintenance volume (mL/24 h)</strong> = hourly
                  rate × 24.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator automatically converts pounds to kilograms if
                needed and shows both hourly and 24‑hour volumes. For very large
                adolescents, many clinicians cap weight at 60 kg for maintenance
                calculations; you can approximate this by entering 60 kg if your
                local guideline recommends a cap.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Maintenance rate factor (e.g. 80% or 50%)</h3>
              <p>
                Not all children should receive 100% of calculated maintenance.
                Conditions associated with non‑osmotic ADH release (e.g.
                post‑operative state, CNS infections, bronchiolitis, pain,
                nausea) often require reduced rates to avoid fluid overload and
                hyponatremia.
              </p>
              <p>
                The <strong>maintenance rate factor</strong> lets you apply a
                percentage to the Holliday–Segar rate:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  \( \text{Adjusted maintenance (mL/hr)} = \text{Holliday–Segar
                  rate} \times \frac{\text{factor %}}{100} \)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>Common choices:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>100%</strong> – typical otherwise well child without
                  SIADH risk.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>80%</strong> – often used in hospitalized children at
                  risk of water retention.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>50%</strong> – for significant cardiac or renal
                  impairment, or when substantial other fluids are being given.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Dehydration deficit calculation</h3>
              <p>
                The calculator estimates fluid deficit from the degree of
                dehydration. A simple bedside approximation is that
                <strong>1% dehydration ≈ 10 mL/kg</strong> of fluid loss.
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Deficit volume (mL)</strong> ≈ weight (kg) ×
                  dehydration % × 10
                </p>
                <p>
                  Example: 12 kg child, 7.5% dehydration → 12 × 7.5 × 10 = 900
                  mL deficit.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                You can choose how quickly to replace this deficit (e.g. over 4,
                8, 24, or 48 hours). The calculator then computes an
                <strong>additional hourly rate</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Deficit rate (mL/hr)</strong> = deficit volume (mL) ÷
                  replacement period (hours)
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>The <strong>total planned rate</strong> is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p>
                  <strong>Total rate (mL/hr)</strong> = adjusted maintenance
                  rate + deficit rate
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                In practice, initial boluses for shock (e.g. 10–20 mL/kg
                isotonic fluid) are given separately and are <em>not</em> part
                of this maintenance/deficit plan.
              </p>

              <h3>4. Choice of IV fluid</h3>
              <p>
                Modern guidelines favor
                <strong>isotonic solutions with dextrose</strong> for most
                hospitalized children to reduce the risk of hyponatremia. A
                commonly recommended composition is:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>0.9% NaCl (normal saline) or balanced isotonic solution</li>
                <li>+ 5% dextrose</li>
                <li>
                  + 20 mmol/L KCl (if adequate urine output and no hyperkalemia)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Hypotonic fluids (e.g. 0.18% or 0.45% NaCl) are generally
                avoided for routine maintenance unless specifically indicated
                and carefully monitored. Always follow your institution’s
                protocol.
              </p>

              <h3>Worked example</h3>
              <p>
                <strong>Scenario:</strong> 3‑year‑old child, weight 14 kg,
                moderate dehydration (~7.5%), plan to replace deficit over 24
                hours, use 80% maintenance.
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Maintenance (Holliday–Segar)</strong><br />
                  Weight 14 kg (between 10–20 kg):<br />
                  Hourly rate = 40 mL/hr + 2 × (14 − 10) = 40 + 8 = 48 mL/hr.<br />
                  Daily maintenance = 48 × 24 = 1152 mL/24 h.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Apply 80% factor</strong><br />
                  Adjusted maintenance = 48 × 0.8 = 38.4 ≈ 38 mL/hr.<br />
                  Daily ≈ 38 × 24 = 912 mL/24 h.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Deficit</strong><br />
                  Dehydration 7.5% → deficit = 14 × 7.5 × 10 = 1050 mL.<br />
                  Over 24 h → 1050 ÷ 24 ≈ 44 mL/hr.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Total planned rate</strong><br />
                  Total = 38 + 44 ≈ 82 mL/hr.<br />
                  Total 24‑h volume ≈ (912 + 1050) = 1962 mL.
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator performs these steps automatically and displays
                maintenance, deficit, and total rates, plus a brief note about
                isotonic fluid choice.
              </p>

              <h3>Clinical caveats and safety</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool is <strong>not</strong> for neonates in the first
                  days of life or for critically ill children in intensive care.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Always adjust for ongoing losses (vomiting, diarrhea, drains)
                  and enteral intake.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Reduce rates and/or change fluid composition in cardiac,
                  renal, or hepatic impairment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Monitor weight, urine output, serum sodium, and overall fluid
                  balance regularly.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Follow local and national pediatric fluid guidelines and
                  consult senior clinicians when in doubt.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>

              <h3>When should I use 80% or 50% of maintenance?</h3>
              <p>
                Many centers routinely prescribe 70–80% of calculated
                maintenance for hospitalized children at risk of SIADH (e.g. CNS
                infections, post‑operative state, pulmonary disease). A 50% rate
                may be appropriate in significant cardiac or renal dysfunction,
                or when substantial other fluids are being given (e.g. enteral
                feeds, drug infusions).
              </p>

              <h3>How often should I reassess the fluid plan?</h3>
              <p>
                Reassess at least every 4–6 hours in acutely unwell children, or
                more frequently if there are changes in clinical status, urine
                output, or laboratory values. Adjust the plan based on evolving
                weight, input/output charts, and serum electrolytes.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this calculator for oral rehydration?</h3>
              <p>
                The formulas are based on IV fluid therapy. For mild to moderate
                dehydration, oral rehydration solutions are often preferred,
                using weight‑based volumes over 3–4 hours. You can still use the
                deficit estimate as a rough guide to total fluid needs, but
                follow specific oral rehydration protocols for dosing and
                timing.
              </p>

              <p class="text-xs text-gray-500 mt-6">
                Disclaimer: This calculator is for educational and
                decision‑support purposes only and does not constitute medical
                advice. Always follow your local guidelines and use clinical
                judgment.
              </p>
